      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 1-month-old infant is brought to the clinic by their mother due to symptoms of fever and lethargy. Upon examination, the infant is found to have an enlarged liver and spleen. The mother reports having a cat at home and mentions that she consumed undercooked meat during her pregnancy. Given this history and the clinical findings, which congenital infection is most likely?</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2861943",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33016,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        13
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B) Congenital Toxoplasmosis.</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Congenital Toxoplasmosis</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> is caused by the<strong> protozoan parasite Toxoplasma gondii</strong>, which can be transmitted to a <strong>developing foetus</strong> if the<strong> mother becomes infected during pregnancy. </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Symptoms&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">in infants may include <strong>fever, lethargy, hepatosplenomegaly and jaundice.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The mother&#39;s history of <strong>owning a cat and consuming undercooked meat during pregnancy</strong> are risk factors for <strong>acquiring</strong> <strong>toxoplasmosis.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Option A:</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Congenital Syphilis</strong> may also present with <strong>fever and hepatosplenomegaly, </strong>but it&rsquo;s typically associated with characteristic <strong>skin rash, bone abnormalities, and other specific clinical features. </strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C: Congenital HIV</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> may present with similar symptoms, but it&rsquo;s usually diagnosed by <strong>routine screening of the mother</strong> during pregnancy. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D: Congenital Cytomegalovirus</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> may cause a range of symptoms including <strong>fever, hepatosplenomegaly, and neurological abnormalities,</strong> but it&rsquo;s typically associated with<strong> hearing loss.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The history of exposure to a <strong>cat and the consumption of undercooked meat during pregnancy, </strong>combined with the <strong>infant&#39;s</strong> <strong>presentation of fever, lethargy, and hepatosplenomegaly,</strong> strongly suggest<strong> congenital toxoplasmosis.</strong> <strong>Cats</strong> are known to be <strong>definitive hosts</strong> for <strong>Toxoplasma gondii</strong>, and undercooked meat is a common source of infection. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Congenital toxoplasmosis</strong> can result from the <strong>transplacental transmission of the parasite</strong> when a woman is infected during <strong>pregnancy.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref:</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Nelson 20<sup>th</sup> Edition, Page No-1723-1725.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
